{"key":"processedPost-20133500","value":{"id":20133500,"first":20133077,"last":20133505,"when":1402846986,"utime":"06/15/14 06:43 PM","content":"The freezing water tells them the season is over and it's time to go dormant for the winter.&nbsp; This is why around 45F to 50F is perfect for cold shocking.&nbsp; It tells them cold weather is coming so they better act busy.<br />You probably can't do shiitake during the summer in those temps.&nbsp; Grow elm oysters or something heat tolerant and grow your shiitake during the winter months.&nbsp; In my location, I can grow them outdoors all summer because even when we get into the 90s during the day, it still drops to the lower 40s at night.&nbsp; I can take blocks straight from colonization to a shady spot along the creek and they fruit right away.<br />The blocks below are spent substrates of varying ages that were put by the creek, where they fruit for several years until the sawdust is completely consumed.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-27/163947372-outdoor_shiitake.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/12-27/163947372-thumb_outdoor_shiitake.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-32/437029127-Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate3.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/12-32/437029127-thumb_Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate3.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-32/437029090-Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/12-32/437029090-thumb_Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: Soaking shiitake sawdust blocks"}}